entry.name: Win_Service_Select_Groovy
entry.description:
Monitors state of Windows Services
- It automatically erases instances that no longer match the filters applied - Discovers only instances set to 'Automatically' start

attribute.name: scriptgroovy
__filter_0
attribute.comment: Services to include, set as property on device.

attribute.name: __filter_1
attribute.comment: Services to exclude, set as property on device.

datapoint.name: State
datapoint.alertbody: The Windows service ##INSTANCE## ##DSIDESCRIPTION## on ##HOST## is not running. This started at ##START## - or ##DURATION## ago.
datapoint.description: Current state of the base service.

datapoint.name: RunningStatus
datapoint.alertbody: The windows service ##INSTANCE## ##DSIDESCRIPTION## on ##HOST## is running, but not in the OK state. It may be in error, degraded or starting/stoppingstate. This started at ##START## - or ##DURATION## ago.
datapoint.description: If service is running, alert if Status is not OK.

datapoint.name: HANDLECOUNT
datapoint.description: Total number of open handles owned by the process. HandleCount is the sum of the handles currently open by each thread in this process. A handle is used to examine or modify the system resources. Each handle has an entry in a table that is maintained internally. Entries contain the addresses of the resources and data to identify the resource type.

datapoint.name: KERNELMODETIME
datapoint.description: Time in kernel mode, in milliseconds. If this information is not available, use a value of 0 (zero). UOM: 100 nanoseconds.

datapoint.name: MAXIMUMWORKINGSETSIZE
datapoint.description: Maximum working set size of the process. The working set of a process is the set of memory pages visible to the process in physical RAM. These pages are resident, and available for an application to use without triggering a page fault. UOM: kilobytes

datapoint.name: MINIMUMWORKINGSETSIZE
datapoint.description: Minimum working set size of the process. The working set of a process is the set of memory pages visible to the process in physical RAM. These pages are resident and available for an application to use without triggering a page fault. UOM: kilobytes

datapoint.name: OTHEROPERATIONCOUNT
datapoint.description: Number of I/O operations performed that are not read or write operations.

datapoint.name: OTHERTRANSFERCOUNT
datapoint.description: Amount of data transferred during operations that are not read or write operations.

datapoint.name: PAGEFAULTS
datapoint.description: Number of page faults that a process generates.

datapoint.name: PAGEFILEUSAGE
datapoint.description: Amount of page file space that a process is using currently. This value is consistent with the VMSize value in TaskMgr.exe. UOM: kilobytes

datapoint.name: PARENTPROCESSID
datapoint.description: Unique identifier of the process that creates a process. Process identifier numbers are reused, so they only identify a process for the lifetime of that process. It is possible that the process identified by ParentProcessId is terminated, so ParentProcessId may not refer to a running process. It is also possible that ParentProcessId incorrectly refers to a process that reuses a process identifier. You can use the CreationDate property to determine whether the specified parent was created after the process represented by this Win32_Process instance was created.

datapoint.name: PEAKPAGEFILEUSAGE
datapoint.description: Maximum virtual address space a process uses at any one time. Using virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. However, virtual space is finite, and by using too much the process might not be able to load libraries. UOM: kilobytes

datapoint.name: PEAKVIRTUALSIZE
datapoint.description: Maximum virtual address space a process uses at any one time. Using virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. However, virtual space is finite, and by using too much the process might not be able to load libraries. UOM: bytes

datapoint.name: PEAKWORKINGSETSIZE
datapoint.description: Peak working set size of a process in kilobytes. UOM: kilobytes

datapoint.name: PRIORITY
datapoint.description: Scheduling priority of a process within an operating system. The higher the value, the higher priority a process receives. Priority values can range from 0 (zero), which is the lowest priority to 31, which is highest priority.

datapoint.name: PRIVATEPAGECOUNT
datapoint.description: Current number of pages allocated that are only accessible to the process represented by this Win32_Process instance.

datapoint.name: QUOTANONPAGEDPOOLUSAGE
datapoint.description: Quota amount of nonpaged pool usage for a process.

datapoint.name: QUOTAPAGEDPOOLUSAGE
datapoint.description: Quota amount of paged pool usage for a process.

datapoint.name: QUOTAPEAKNONPAGEDPOOLUSAGE
datapoint.description: Peak quota amount of nonpaged pool usage for a process.

datapoint.name: QUOTAPEAKPAGEDPOOLUSAGE
datapoint.description: Peak quota amount of paged pool usage for a process.

datapoint.name: READOPERATIONCOUNT
datapoint.description: Number of read operations performed.

datapoint.name: READTRANSFERCOUNT
datapoint.description: Amount of data read. UOM: bytes

datapoint.name: SESSIONID
datapoint.description: Unique identifier that an operating system generates when a session is created. A session spans a period of time from logon until logoff from a specific system.

datapoint.name: THREADCOUNT
datapoint.description: Number of active threads in a process. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a processor, and a thread is the object that executes an instruction. Each running process has at least one thread.

datapoint.name: USERMODETIME
datapoint.description: Time in user mode, in 100 nanosecond units. If this information is not available, use a value of 0 (zero). UOM: 100 nanoseconds

datapoint.name: VIRTUALSIZE
datapoint.description: Current size of the virtual address space that a process is using, not the physical or virtual memory actually used by the process. Using virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. Virtual space is finite, and by using too much, the process might not be able to load libraries. This value is consistent with what you see in Perfmon.exe. UOM: bytes

datapoint.name: WORKINGSETSIZE
datapoint.description: Amount of memory in bytes that a process needs to execute efficientlyâ€”for an operating system that uses page-based memory management. If the system does not have enough memory (less than the working set size), thrashing occurs. If the size of the working set is not known, use NULL or 0 (zero). If working set data is provided, you can monitor the information to understand the changing memory requirements of a process. UOM: bytes

datapoint.name: WRITEOPERATIONCOUNT
datapoint.description: Number of write operations performed.

datapoint.name: WRITETRANSFERCOUNT
datapoint.description: Amount of data written. UOM: bytes
